  & Losing one's own things is very irritating – a scarf of all things! A piece of fabric that long could not stay hidden... or so {{Lupin}} thought. The same thing had happened the week before, and the month prior. It excelled at the art of disappearance. Lupin claimed to have nothing to do with it getting lost. The lengthy fiend was sentient no doubt, and enjoyed eluding its master.

  & Lupin could never remember where things were. Worse yet, was that Lupin also liked to borrow things. All {{Verido}} borrowed from one another from time to time, if they saw something they liked in the house of another they would take it without asking, and that was okay. Objects had a way of making the rounds and somehow always ended up back where they'd started — that is, unless Lupin was the borrower. Many objects from homes around the village had never returned, everyone knew who was to blame for it and yet no one came to claim anything back, having found joy in having fewer things. Their dwellings as a result had become more spacious, more pleasant, but Lupin's clutter only worsened. The clutter had become a hazard. some of the village elders did worry, but after much thinking they too chose to ignore it. 

  & Lupin - like all others in the village of {{Volare}} - lived in a tall narrow house. The ground in Volare was never still and so the buildings were tall to allow more flexibility. With every motion the walls cracked without breaking, and the tops swayed dangerously from one side to the other. Lupin liked sleeping from a hammock on the ceiling, accessible by means of a narrow stairway. The hammock would never stop swinging, carried by the constant motion of the world. Overlooking the hammock was a gap in the ceiling, a window equipped with a heavy shutter — which could be drawn down in the event of a storm. With a clearing like this, Lupin could sleep with the stars. Those lights, unlike all earthly objects, were impossible to borrow. The young Verido liked to pretend though, fingers obscuring the edges and narrowing down into a pinch. 

  & On the lower floor was a small kitchen, a cramped area with a pantry, a fire bowl and a cold pot. The fire bowl, like many other objects in the house, was made out of molded carapace shavings. The bowl had left over ashes in it, left over from the last time Lupin had cooked a dinner of grilled {{looma roots}}. The cold pot had another pot inside it, with its outer wall completely covered in sand, in the innermost pot lay fresh {{teaweet}} berries. Then there was the pantry, two long poles stuck out of the ground with braided isilk baskets hanging between. The baskets were used to store dry ingredients, Lupin kept a variety of herbs and root vegetables in these, like Looma roots, {{bibiskiss}} and plumpkins. Secured by the two poles on the ground lay a box with empty sacks of flour. When {{Levi}} was here the sacks were full, every morning they'd make bread puddings and giant domed loaves together. Lupin had fond memories of that time, but this house no longer smelled of baked goods, not since {{Levi}} had died. Lupin's diet now consisted of tea and grilled root vegetables. 

  & Some bottles of tea were steeping outside right now, warmed by the sun. Momentarily forgetting about the scarf, Lupin stepped out and put a nose to a bottle of {{licky root}} tea, judged it to be ready and brought it inside. The drink was syrupy and sweet. The dark circular roots of the plant lay at the bottom of the bottle, heavy with liquid. {{licky root}} was grown right here in the village, Lupin walked to the base of Vol's nape everyday to harvest them. Few plants could thrive up here, the altitude did not permit much, although fungi and small garden herbs were plentiful. 

  & Lupin sighed when seeing the state of the place. The floor of the main room had many objects; pieces of unfinished projects, attempts at honing a skill - any skill. Lupin had tried to learn to knit, but the result was too horrid to wear. The knitted fiasco had instead become the head of a mop, which to this day had seen no action. 

  & Lupin had seen {{Levi}} knit many times, the motions were familiar but these dumb hands could not replicate them. Many skeins lay on the ground, grains of sand mixed into the fibers. This mess was a left over from the last time Lupin had left the overhead window open during a heavy sandstorm. 
  
  & All in the village had a skill, but this young Verido feared to possess none — that is, unless the art of cluttering spaces could be artful in some way. Lupin was short and possessed little body strength, but could beat anyone in a dumpling eating contest, again not an ability that could benefit anyone else in any way. This was the truth behind the compulsive borrowing, born out of Lupin's desire to discover a worthwhile passion.

  & "LOOK AT YOU LEW! All dressed up and fancy-like!" 

  & Lupin spun right around to look at who was there, it was {{Rosmus}}, a friend and resident of Volare. {{Rosmus}} was taller and older than Lupin, with hair standing on end, higher than anyone in the village. A single strand hung low, weighed down by a single blue bead.

  & "I am fancy aren't I?" Lupin was wearing traditional ceremonial wear, a set only worn on special occasions like on Green or Leaping days. The outfit was colorful and had many details and layers to it, Lupin had a necklace of blue thread cascading down over a bear chest, the lower half of the body was covered with a patterned knee-long cloth and superimposed with a woven mat. "I spent all of last night looking for each piece... now if only I could get my hands on that damned scarf."

  & "Your hair looks nice blue!" {{Rosmus}} said, impressed with Lupin's handiwork, "your face paint though is um. Well- it's um, it's unique is what it is!" 

  & It was customary for special events to dye both your hair and face blue, using the crushed pigments of the of the fruit of the {{looberry}} plant. "I ran out of looberries about halfway into it."

  & "It's fine, people will just assume you've forgotten to finish it, which is okay, people expect that from you so it's completely in character. Anyway! I got this for you! A gift!" The visitor was dressed in plain clothes, holding a basket of {{trumpet flower}} sprouts — the stems kept fresh by a layer of earth. "Thought we could hang around here and plant these, in a few months they'll start flowering and you know what that means! Thoughtful of me don't you think? No one else tends to your need for intoxicants like I do."

  & "Your need you mean, you're conscious for about 2 hours a day... it's like your part {{Durdle}}. Hey–Don't you know what today is?"

  & "Sure I do, but I'm not going and neither are you." {{Rosmus}} said.

  & Lupin laughed at these words. "I'm not gonna sit here with you waiting for the plants to grow."

  & "Why not? I also brought some {{kabacho}} to drink! It's been steeping for a year! It's going to be real strong." {{Rosmus}} held a bottle of red liquid, with a wrinkly fruit floating inside it. 

  & "They're expecting me Ros, the whole town is! As much as I'd like to just sit around and drink all day I've got to go! I don't have a choice, you know that."

  & "You DO have a choice." {{Rosmus}} corrected. "You think you don't, but you can do whatever you want! It's all up to you! Come on don't you think it'd be more fun to do this instead?"

  & "Ceremony's more important I think..."

  & "So they say..." {{Rosmus}} said, "why go at all? I mean, you already know you won't be named Voice so... why bother?"

  & "Tradition."

  & "Right. Don't you think it unfair though? To be part of a contest with a predetermined result? {{Mago}}'s family has always been Voice, since Volare's time and that's not about to change. When you think about it, there's really no point in you being there at all! If I were you, I'd stay here. Come on, give me a mug that I can fill."

  & "It's just like you to say something like that." Lupin said, busy upturning the place, lifting every book. Lupin did find other things thought to be lost, but these stayed in their spot, to be forgotten and rediscovered again at a later more convenient time. "I've got to be there. That's all. Don't ask me again."

  & {{Rosmus}}, lacking a mug, took a sip of kabacho from the bottle instead. "Oh—OH! SO strong. Wow! Oh gosh my lips are numb!" {{Rosmus}} struggled for a moment to finish a thought, having much trouble getting the lips and tongue to cooperate. "So... you're alright with pretending you can win this."

  & "I'm not pretending! AH–It doesn't matter! I'm fine with it is what I'm saying." Lupin moved to the other side of the room to peer behind a table. "AH! It's here! I've found it!" The long blue scarf had been hiding there this whole time, wedged between the table and the wall. Lupin put the scarf on, coiling it tight. "I wouldn't make a good Voice, {{Mago}}'s better than me in every way."

  & "Did you ever think that maybe you're always underperforming because you know you can't win? That whatever you do won't change the outcome, so you know... why try?" {{Rosmus}}'s lips had turned a bright red color then, another effect of the kabacho.

  & "I'll find something else I'm good at... eventually. I'll see it more clearly when this thing is over. I know it."

  & {{Rosmus}} set the kabacho on the ground, then found an amusing hat and decided to keep it. Ros then picked up a {{koutra}} from the floor and tried to play it. "Bit out of tune, won't be impressing anyone with an out of tune {{koutra}}."

  & "Yea. It did sound pretty terrible." Lupin said with a sigh, eyeing the stringed instrument. "Look. I've got to go." The Verido began to move toward the door, stepping in between objects to get to it, then came up to the bottle of {{kabacho}} and decided to take a sip. "For my nerves," Lupin said.

  & "Hey! What if you actually did become Voice? That would be something wouldn't it?" {{Rosmus}} yelled. "Imagine! If you were Voice you wouldn't be breaking anyone's ears anymore!"

  & Lupin gave {{Rosmus}} a mean look before breaking into a run, the town centre was near but the sun was high now, any moment now the ceremony would start.

